@node "Introduction" "Introduction to Index View"

  @{b}@{u}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

  MCallSign is a small utility, which allows to search country in few
databases (BERU, CQWW, DXCC, HOLY, PACC, R150S, REF, REFDX, RSGB, SAC,
SEANET, UBA)

  Main features of MCallSign:
    - Database files is in pure CSV format so there's no problem to edit
      it and update. I made these files from HTML files. Also is
      possible to use files ".CTY" from SuperDuper (PC logbook
      by EI5DI) but only after convert it by sdconv program (included).
    - Can display informations about prefix with main prefix,
      ITU and WAZ zone, continent and so on.
    - Magic User Interface.
    - It's freeware.
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Index View Requirements"

  @{b}@{u}Requirements@{ub}@{uu}

  MLocator should run on any Amiga with Kickstart 2.0+ but you should
have some more CPU power than 68000. On 68020 with Fast MCallSign is very
slow. I think the reason of it is not fast procedure to searching
databases but I have'nt a time to fix it now. MCallSign should work even
with 512KB of memory. I tested this program on A1200 with:

BlizzardPPC 603e+/200MHz/060/50MHz and 64MB.
@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

  @{b}@{u}Installation@{ub}@{uu}

  Have you a problem with it ?
@endnode

@node "Usage" "How to use Index View"

  @{b}@{u}Usage@{ub}@{uu}

      You can select CallSign string field by click mouse button and
  type on keyboard any callsign. If you wrote something in string field
  you have to press "ENTER" key.
  Field "Country criterion" (default CQWW) allows you change database
  with callsigns based on another rules than CQWW. For example if you
  like to check your QSO's with DXCC list it's very simple to do it.
@endnode

@node "Update" "Update"

  @{b}@{u}Update@{ub}@{uu}

  You can find newer versions of SuperDuper on:

  @{b}http://www.ei5di.com/@{ub}

  then unarchive it and convert all ".cty" files to ".csv" by sdconv
program (included to MCallSign archivum). e.g.

  @{b}sdconv from cqww.cty to cqww.csv@{ub}

  New DXCC list you can find here:

  @{b}http://www.cpcug.org/user/wfeidt/Dxcc/@{ub}

  You must download HTML and convert it to pure ASCII text. See into
orginal files.
@endnode

